---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith("/")
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Dreamwork with Jane | Still Ground"
  description="Gentle, spacious dreamwork sessions with Jane Aldiss online worldwide or in person in North Norfolk."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Dreamwork with Jane</p>
      <h1>What the dreaming mind is trying to tell you</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Dreams carry information that the waking mind has not yet found words
        for. Working with them gently, and without agenda, can be a direct route
        into self-understanding.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <a class="button" href="mailto:hello@stillground.co.uk">Ask Jane about dreamwork</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href={`${base}personal-retreats/`}>Personal retreats</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <figure class="hero-media image-contain">
      <img
        src={`${base}assets/dreamwork/blue-dreaming.webp`}
        alt="A blue dreamlike image of a resting face and mountain forms"
        width="900"
        height="570"
        decoding="async"
        fetchpriority="high"
      />
      <figcaption>Dreamwork</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="statement">
    <p>
      A dreamwork session is a conversation. You bring the dream, however
      fragmentary, strange, or fleeting, and Jane sits with it alongside you.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Spacious, unhurried exploration</p>
      <h2>The meaning lives in you</h2>
      <p>
        Through careful listening and reflective questioning, you begin to
        discover what the images mean to you.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not analysis. There is no dream dictionary, and no clever
        interpretation imposed from the outside. The work is in uncovering what
        is already held within the dreamer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Dreams often address precisely what is most alive in waking life: a
        decision unmade, a relationship that needs attention, or a feeling that
        has not been named yet. The insights that emerge tend to be both
        surprising and immediately recognisable, as though something already
        known is finally being said clearly.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="note-panel">
      <p class="small-label">Simple and flexible</p>
      <ul class="list-clean">
        <li>Session length: one hour.</li>
        <li>Available online worldwide.</li>
        <li>In-person sessions take place in North Norfolk.</li>
        <li>Dreamwork can be woven into a personal retreat in Aylsham.</li>
        <li>Cost: please get in touch and Jane can discuss it with you.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="feature-grid" aria-label="What to expect">
    <article>
      <h3>Deep listening</h3>
      <p>
        You will be heard carefully and without judgement. There is no right way
        to tell a dream.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Reflective questioning</h3>
      <p>
        Gentle questions help you find your own way into the dream's meaning.
        Nothing is imposed.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>Patterns over time</h3>
      <p>
        Recurring images and figures often carry important messages. Working
        across several sessions allows threads to emerge that a single
        conversation cannot.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">When you might reach out</p>
      <h2>Curiosity is enough</h2>
      <p>
        Some people arrive with a single dream that will not leave them alone.
        Others have been curious about their dreaming life for years but have
        not found the right space to explore it. Some are in the middle of a
        transition or a loss and find that their dreams are speaking to it
        directly.
      </p>
      <p>
        You do not need to be a vivid dreamer. You do not need any background in
        psychology or spiritual practice. You need only a willingness to stay
        curious.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="soft-panel">
      <p class="small-label">Good reasons to come</p>
      <ul class="list-clean">
        <li>A recurring dream or image you cannot shake.</li>
        <li>A life transition that needs more than talking through.</li>
        <li>Wanting to know yourself better, without a programme to follow.</li>
        <li>Curiosity about what your dreaming mind is carrying.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-narrow">
    <p class="eyebrow">Jane's practice</p>
    <h2>Forty years of practice. Dreams as a living part of it.</h2>
    <p>
      Jane's engagement with dreams has been lifelong. Formal training came
      later: a certification in Dream Yoga, followed by ongoing study that has
      taken her in a more Tibetan direction over time.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 2021 Jane had a dream that changed the direction of her practice. The
      face of a Tibetan lama appeared, in a Himalayan monastery. A few weeks
      later, following an unexpected thread of synchronicities, she walked down
      a forest track 500 miles from home and found a Buddhist retreat centre.
      When she looked it up, there was the face from the dream. That experience
      led her to meet her current meditation teacher and begin travelling to his
      centres in Nepal and worldwide.
    </p>
    <p>
      Jane shares this not to make dreamwork sound mysterious, but because it is
      true. Dreams can be very precise. Working with someone who has experienced
      this directly feels different from working with someone who has only read
      about it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Common questions</p>
    <h2>Before you book</h2>
    <div class="schedule">
      <article>
        <h3>What if I do not remember my dreams?</h3>
        <p>
          This comes up often. Jane has several approaches for working with
          people who rarely or never remember their dreams, including ways of
          working that do not require a specific dream to begin with. It is
          worth getting in touch even if your dreaming life feels elusive.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Do I need any background in this?</h3>
        <p>None at all. Come as you are.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>How many sessions will I need?</h3>
        <p>
          A single session can be genuinely useful. Most people find that
          working across a few sessions allows patterns to emerge that one
          conversation cannot. There is no minimum commitment.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Is this therapy?</h3>
        <p>
          No. This sits within contemplative self-inquiry. It is not therapy,
          counselling, or clinical mental health support. If you have concerns
          about your mental health, Jane will help you find the right
          professional support.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <h3>Can this be part of a personal retreat?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes. Dreamwork sessions can be shaped into a weekend retreat in
          Aylsham alongside meditation, nourishing food, and plenty of time to
          simply be.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="contact-band">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Free introductory call</p>
      <h2>No preparation needed</h2>
      <p>
        Come with a dream, a question, or simply a feeling that this might be
        the right time.
      </p>
    </div>
    <a class="button" href="mailto:hello@stillground.co.uk">Email Jane</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
